Loading the dataset of faces¶

  • Taken from AT&T Laboratories Cambridge: http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/research/dtg/attarchive/facedatabase.htmlTen

  • Different images of each of 40 distinct subjects

  • Some images were taken at different times, varying the lighting, facial expressions (open / closed eyes, smiling / not smiling) and facial details (glasses / no glasses).
  • All the images were taken against a dark homogeneous background with the subjects in an upright, frontal position (with tolerance for some side movement).

PCA Step 1: Subtract the mean face to center the image data¶

As the illustration here shows, before we find a new representation of the data in a new coordinate system, we first need to center the new set of axis on the data set.

This is done by subtracting the average face from each image vector. Let $x_{k}^{(i)}$ represent the $k^{th}$ pixel value in the $i^{th}$ image vector. Then the $k^{th}$ pixel value in the mean face is $\overline{x}_{k} = \dfrac{1}{n}\Sigma_{i=0}^{n}x_{k}^{(i)}$.

In [9]:

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))

Step 2: Create the Covariance Matrix¶

-The sample covariance of two ramdom variables is defined by

$Cov(X,Y) = \dfrac{1}{n-1}\Sigma(X-\overline{X})(Y-\overline{Y})$

where $\overline{X}$ and $\overline{Y}$ are the sample averages of $X$ and $Y$, respectively.

-The 2x2 covariance matrix is given by \begin{bmatrix} Cov(X,X) & Cov(X,Y) \\ Cov(Y,X) & Cov(Y,Y) \end{bmatrix}

-If the matrix $B$ has columns of the form $x^{(i)} - \overline{x}$, where $x^{(i)}$ is feature vector with length n_features, and $\overline{x}$ is the average of all feature vectors, then $\dfrac{1}{n-1}B^tB$ is an $n $ x $n$ covariance matrix for all the features in the data.

In [11]:
reshaped = Xtrain_centered.reshape(320, 4096)

covariance = 1.0/319*np.dot(np.transpose(reshaped), reshaped)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
In [16]:
'''
Compute a PCA (eigenfaces) on the dataset (treated as unlabeled
dataset): unsupervised feature extraction / dimensionality reduction
'''

n_components = 320    # number of components (eigenvectors to keep)

print("Extracting the top %d eigenfaces from %d faces..."
      % (n_components, Xtrain.shape[0]))
t0 = time()


pca_faces = PCA(n_components=n_components, svd_solver='randomized',
          whiten=True).fit(Xtrain)


print("Done in %0.3fs." % (time() - t0))

Extracting the top 320 eigenfaces from 320 faces...
Done in 0.339s.

Some questions come up now that we have a set of eigenfaces: Are some eigenfaces "better" than others? Do certain faces describe the variation in the dataset better than others?

The answer here is yes in the second question. The diagonal entries of the diagonalized covariance matric represents the variance of each eigenface, yet it is also the eingenvalue. Therefore, the eigenface with largest eigenvalue represents the facial component that varies the most in the data. The images in our dataset contain large (positive and negative) multiples of this eigenface.

From Faces to an Eigenface Representation¶

In [18]:
def normed_image(a):
    return (a - a.min())/(a.max() -a.min())

def get_normed_component(pc, j):
    size = 64*64
    g = pc.components_[j][0:size]
    g = normed_image(g)
    return g

def display_component(pc, j):
    g = get_normed_component(pc,j)
    print(g.shape)
    plt.imshow(g.reshape(64, 64), cmap='gray')
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

# Approximate a new face using the mean face and Eigenfaces

eigenfaces = pca_faces.components_
approximation = np.zeros(4096)

for i in range(len(eigenfaces)):
    weight = np.dot(test_face, eigenfaces[i])    
    approximation += eigenfaces[i] * weight

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))
plt.imshow(approximation.reshape(64,64), cmap='gray')

How accurate is the eigenface representation? Can we do better?¶

  • Most broad features are captured (face shape, position of eyes, mouth, etc), but not the fine details.

  • We should try PCA on a larger dataset with more human subjects. Using a dataset of 10 similar-looking pictures of 40 different people may not have introduced enough variation.

Further use cases to be researched:¶

  • Using PCA and classification algorithms for facial detection
  • Using Eigenfaces as image compression
